{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474224"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:18:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:18:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11845"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11845"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.03,0.11,0.11,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4446"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53671"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4446"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11845"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39139"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1662"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6415"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6425"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16064"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53671"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent. The parent reports that the child has been experiencing headaches for the past six months and has been struggling academically. The child has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. No obvious abnormalities are noted on general examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Refractive error","Congenital cataract","Strabismus","Congenital glaucoma","Optic nerve hypoplasia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely explanation for this child\u0027s presentation is a \u003Cstrong\u003Erefractive error\u003C/strong\u003E. Refractive errors are the most common cause of decreased vision in children and young adults. Children often struggle to articulate visual problems, which can manifest as headaches, academic difficulties, or behavioural changes. In this case, the combination of headaches and academic struggles, without other significant findings, strongly suggests an uncorrected refractive error.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital cataracts\u003C/strong\u003E are typically identified much earlier in life, often shortly after birth or in infancy. They cause opacification of the lens, leading to more severe and noticeable visual impairment than what is described in this case. The late presentation and the nature of symptoms make congenital cataracts an unlikely explanation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStrabismus\u003C/strong\u003E (squint) can sometimes be a result of uncorrected refractive error, but it is not typically a primary cause of decreased vision on its own. Strabismus would likely be noticeable on examination and would usually be picked up earlier, either by parents or during routine health checks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare condition that typically presents with more severe symptoms in early infancy, such as excessive tearing, light sensitivity, and enlargement of the eye (buphthalmos). The age of onset and the nature of symptoms in this case do not align with congenital glaucoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOptic nerve hypoplasia\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital defect where the optic nerve does not fully develop. It usually causes more significant visual impairment from birth or early infancy and is often associated with other midline brain malformations or systemic conditions. The presentation at age six with relatively mild symptoms makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the prevalence of refractive errors and the presentation described, a comprehensive eye examination, including refraction, is the most appropriate next step. Early detection and correction of refractive errors are crucial to prevent potential complications such as amblyopia (lazy eye) and to support the child\u0027s academic and social development.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Refractive errors are the most common cause of decreased vision in children and can present with headaches and academic difficulties.","A comprehensive eye examination is essential for children presenting with headaches, even if the primary referral reason is not vision-related."],"references":["Childhood Eye Diseases and Conditions. Childhood Eye Diseases and Conditions [Internet]. American Academy of Ophthalmology. 2013. Available from: https://www.aao.org/eye-health/tips-prevention/common-childhood-diseases-conditions","\u200cAkinci A, G\u00fcven A, Degerliyurt A, Kibar E, Mutlu M, Citirik M. The correlation between headache and refractive errors. Journal of the American Association for Pediatric Ophthalmology and Strabismus (JAAPOS). 2008;12(3):290-3. Available at: https://www.jaapos.org/article/S1091-8531(07)00580-0/abstract"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39139"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11845"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39139"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2